body:
@erichmenge - I see your point

@rafaelfranca - This is not only useful for `from`, but also for things like `replay_to` or `return_path`. The initial implementation was focused on `from` because IMHO this is the most popular usecase (according to my experiences). However afer @josevalim remarks I changed it so that more headers can be set, not only `from`. I am not 100% sure but I think this is also useful when you want custom default header in every email like `X-RailsIsAwesome`.

And finally let me remind you that this implementation is basically 1-liner now: https://github.com/paneq/rails/commit/dd1b6f679af1c6e6ea8af655860ac0c96627a028#L0R416

And I think it makes sense to have this so that `config/application.rb` can be coherent:

```ruby
config.action_mailer.default_url_options = { :host => "example.org", :protocol => "https" }
config.action_mailer.default_options = {:from => "newsletter@example.org"}
```

instead of

```ruby
config.action_mailer.default_url_options = { :host => "example.org", :protocol => "https" }
ActionMailer::Base.default_options = {:from => "newsletter@example.org"}
```

Last word: Nobody is forcing you to use this feature. I you prefer to inherit from `ApplicationMailer`, that's ok. I just think that some people would like to do it they way I presented and to allow it we just need 1 line of code. I think it is fair price for this "feature".
